com.itko.lisa.test

Class TestCase

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.itko.lisa.LisaDocInfo
      • com.itko.lisa.test.TestCase
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.itko.lisa.model.IWriteXML, java.io.Serializable

    public class TestCase
extends com.itko.lisa.LisaDocInfo
implements com.itko.lisa.model.IWriteXML
    This class contains the object form of the test case that is stored as a document somewhere. One of the first things LISA must do to prepare a test for execution is construct a TestCase object out of the document.

    All test info is stored here:

    • meta (version and build number)
    • name
    • nodes in the test
    • references to the datasets
    • random sets
    • filters

    Note that no test execution specific state is stored here. Objects of this type are serialized and sent to the Simulators for execution. A separate type called the TestExec holds session data.

    To run a test case directly from the command line with only one instance and run from the machine that you are running the command prompt, you can execute this class. See the usage() method or run this class with -h for help on the parameters required.

    There are 2 programmatic ways to execute a test. Most uses of the TestCase run are like this:

    • Construct the TestCase
    • Construct a TestExec
    • Here, either run inline or interactively:
    • inline by running the test completely by calling TestCase.executeTest()
    • OR
      • call setupTestCase()
      • then call executeNextNode() until you get false back
      • at any time you need to, you can call gets on TestExec for current state
      • then call endTest() when you are done
    See Also:
    TestExec, Serialized Form

      • prepare

        public void prepare()
             throws LisaException
        This method _must_ be called by any engine that is going to execute the test, but must do so in the same process space that will actually execute. Let's back up...

        You can construct a TestCase object anywhere you like, and from whatever means. And TestCase objects are serializable so they can be sent wherever you want them to go.

        This is good, but creates a problem for the nodes within the test. They might need to do one-time initialization that must prepare the system that will run them, not just load them. That's one of the reasons this method exists.

        Throws:
        TestRunException
        LisaException

      • executeTest

        public void executeTest(TestExec ts)
        This is the typical way you run a test. Construct this TestCase, then construct a TestExec for a specific run state, then call this method. This will run the test to completion.

        The other way is interacitvely, by calling setupTestRun() and then calling executeNextNode() until there is no next node.

        This method doesn't return until the test cycle is complete.

        Parameters:
        ts - this is the TestExec object that represents the state

        See Also:
        TestExec
